  "prompt": "How does evolution is supported by the fossil record?",
  "response": "The fossil record provides strong evidence for evolution in several ways:\n\n1. Transitional fossils\n- Show gradual changes between species\n- Demonstrate evolutionary intermediates\n- Examples: Archaeopteryx (between dinosaurs and birds), Tiktaalik (fish to amphibian transition)\n\n2. Chronological progression\n- Fossils are arranged in rock layers from oldest to youngest\n- More complex organisms appear in later layers\n- Shows gradual development of life forms over time\n\n3. Shared characteristics\n- Fossils of related species show similar anatomical structures\n- Indicates common ancestry and gradual modifications\n\n4. Extinct species\n- Reveal organisms that no longer exist\n- Demonstrate how species change or become extinct over time\n\n5. Biogeographical distribution\n- Fossil records show how species spread and adapted to different environments\n- Explains migration and diversification patterns\n\n6. Comparative anatomy\n- Fossils reveal homologous structures across different species\n- Suggests evolutionary relationships\n\n7. Genetic similarities\n- Fossil evidence often correlates with genetic studies\n- Provides additional support for evolutionary relationships\n\nThese lines of evidence collectively demonstrate how species have changed and diversified over millions of years, supporting the theory of evolution through natural selection.",
